00:00:20.027 --> 00:00:21.860
PROFESSOR: So, any
questions from last time?

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:27.090
We started doing
reaction mechanisms.

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:33.430
We did first order
parallel reactions.

00:00:33.430 --> 00:00:35.280
So one of the things
that we'll be stressing

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:39.630
is that the mechanisms
that we write down

00:00:39.630 --> 00:00:46.560
are ways to try to understand
a complicated chemical process.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:53.510
And you take data, you can
find intermediates sometimes.

00:00:53.510 --> 00:00:56.740
And you get rate
laws from the data.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:58.220
You infer rate laws.

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:01.470
And from these rate
laws, you think up

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:08.890
of a reaction mechanism and you
make sure that what you measure

00:01:08.890 --> 00:01:10.460
is consistent with
your mechanism

00:01:10.460 --> 00:01:15.051
that you make up to explain the
complicated chemical process.

00:01:15.051 --> 00:01:16.800
And one really important
thing to remember

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:20.860
is that when you come
up with a mechanism

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:25.800
and you've got a bunch of data
that supports it, it's great.

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:29.270
But it doesn't mean that
you've solve the problem.

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.400
It doesn't mean
that you've proven

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:35.280
that the way that the
chemistry proceeds

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:36.780
is really the way it proceeds.

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:40.822
Because there's
always the possibility

00:01:40.822 --> 00:01:42.780
that there's an intermediate
somewhere in there

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:45.930
that you haven't
been able to measure.

00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:48.280
And a lot of people
got tripped up

00:01:48.280 --> 00:01:51.500
over the course of
the last century,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:55.700
of making up mechanisms, getting
a lot of data that supports

00:01:55.700 --> 00:02:01.760
the mechanism and missing
something really important.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:04.350
So it's a common
mistake, that people

00:02:04.350 --> 00:02:07.660
think they've proven
a particular chemical

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:12.880
mechanism just because they
have data that supports it.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:15.450
It's up to a certain point
that you know what you have.

00:02:15.450 --> 00:02:20.330
And we'll see examples
of that today, probably.

00:02:20.330 --> 00:02:22.660
And then certainly
next time when

00:02:22.660 --> 00:02:25.000
we start making approximations
in our kinetics.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:27.990
And see where things
can really go wrong

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:30.600
if you don't have enough data.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:32.330
If you don't try
to fish out really,

00:02:32.330 --> 00:02:37.680
really, tiny intermediates
somewhere along the way.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.510
So last time we did then
parallel first order reactions.

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:45.980
And today we're going
to march through and do

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:47.960
parallel first and second order.

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:50.180
So one is first order, the
other one is second order.

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:52.260
Things are going to
get more complicated.

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:54.010
And what you're going
to get is a flavor

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:55.950
of how to solve the problems.

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:57.319
Setting up the problems.

00:02:57.319 --> 00:02:59.860
We're not going to do a lot of
the algebra here on the board,

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:02.870
because otherwise we
would spend the next three

00:03:02.870 --> 00:03:04.080
weeks doing algebra.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.095
And that would be no fun at all.

00:03:06.095 --> 00:03:07.470
That doesn't mean
that you're not

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:10.360
going to be doing any
algebra on the homework.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:15.520
Because part of it is
figuring how to do it.

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:22.090
So, we have a reaction
where A goes to B plus C.

00:03:22.090 --> 00:03:24.480
And the first thing we did
was, the first mechanism

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:26.640
we wrote was a parallel
mechanism where

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:34.240
we had A goes B and A goes
to C. That's the mechanism.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:41.810
And one other way to write
it is A goes to B or C,

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:47.810
in a way that is more,
sort of describes

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:49.830
the branching
process, that when we

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:54.810
talk about a branching ratio,
the ratio of amount of B to C,

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:59.020
this looks like the branching
out of two different paths.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:03.520
And this time we're going to
do where this is first order

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:07.620
and this is second order.

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:13.220
With the rate k1 and a rate k2.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:15.150
And the way that you
do all these problems,

00:04:15.150 --> 00:04:18.284
you have to be very
systematic about it.

00:04:18.284 --> 00:04:19.700
The first thing
you do is you have

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:22.240
to write down all
your rate laws.

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:25.470
And make sure that you
include everything.

00:04:25.470 --> 00:04:28.830
So you start by writing the rate
law for the destruction of A.

00:04:28.830 --> 00:04:32.260
And then the rate law for the
appearance of B and for C.

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:33.940
So for a, we have dA/dt.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:36.090
And again, I'm dropping
the brackets around the A,

00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:41.030
because I don't want to carry
around all these extra symbols.

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:47.990
So we destroy A by making B. So
that's going to be first order.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:49.721
And then we also
destroy A by making C,

00:04:49.721 --> 00:04:50.720
and that's second order.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:57.420
So we have two paths out
of A. To get rid of A.

00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:02.660
Then we write down the
appearance of B, dB/dt.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:08.710
It's only through one
path, first order in A,

00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:13.430
and then the appearance
of C, only one path

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:16.305
which is second order.

00:05:16.305 --> 00:05:18.180
And these are all our
differential equations.

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:24.900
And now the trick is, how do you
solve these three differential

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:32.300
equations in a way that you
get meaningful information out.

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:36.490
Well, the first
thing to do is to,

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:41.532
so these two here depend on
A. So the appearance of B

00:05:41.532 --> 00:05:43.490
depends on A, the appearance
of C depends on A.

00:05:43.490 --> 00:05:45.490
But this one here only
depends on A by itself.

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:47.904
So this is the first one
you're going to start out with.

00:05:47.904 --> 00:05:49.320
Because you can
put all of the A's

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:53.530
on one side and all the time on
the other side and integrate.

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:59.340
So then you solve, and
you can rewrite this

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:10.740
as minus dA/dt is equal to
k1 times A times one plus k2

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:16.630
over k1 times A. And then you
put all the A's on one side,

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:18.950
all the t's on the other side.

00:06:18.950 --> 00:06:30.580
And integrate from A0 to A minus
dA over A times one plus k2

00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:39.430
over k1 times A. That is
equal to k1 from zero to t dt.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:41.485
And then you have to
solve this integral here.

00:06:41.485 --> 00:06:44.410
And there's a reason why
I factored out the A here.

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:45.910
It's because this
is of the form you

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:48.810
can use to use the trick
of partial fractions, which

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:51.900
we mentioned this before.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:07:01.650
So you use partial
fractions to solve this.

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:04.380
And I'm not going to
do it on the board.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:06.270
You turn the crank,
you basically

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:09.560
write one over A times
one plus k2 over k1 A

00:07:09.560 --> 00:07:13.184
is equal to n1 of A plus
n2 over this part here,

00:07:13.184 --> 00:07:15.350
and you solve for n1 and
n2 and you plug it back in,

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:18.730
and you redo your
integral, et cetera.

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:19.802
And you get your answer.

00:07:19.802 --> 00:07:21.510
Which I'm going to
write down because I'm

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:29.170
going to use it
later. k1 A0 over e

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:36.195
to the k1 times
t, k1 plus k2 A0.

00:07:36.195 --> 00:07:37.820
So one of the things
we immediately see

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:41.930
is even though this mechanism
isn't very complicated,

00:07:41.930 --> 00:07:45.470
just two paths, one first order,
one second order, the solutions

00:07:45.470 --> 00:07:53.080
start to get not so
simple pretty quickly.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:55.590
So it depends, there's an
exponential on the bottom here.

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:58.700
Depends on the initial
concentrations and both rate

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:02.205
constants are in there.

00:08:02.205 --> 00:08:03.580
The first thing
you want to do is

00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:09.900
you want to look
at limiting cases.

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:12.080
Just like before.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:15.520
We did, and the
first limiting case

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:18.300
we're going to look at,
so interesting to look at

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:22.110
is this guy right
here. k1 and k2 A here.

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:27.870
If one is bigger than the other,
then things will cancel out.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:30.620
And we can get some intuition.

00:08:30.620 --> 00:08:33.270
So the first limiting case
we're going to look at

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:43.961
is where k2 A0, this term right
here, is much smaller than k1.

00:08:43.961 --> 00:08:46.210
Now, we want to make sure
that in these limiting cases

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:49.160
that when I write something like
this, that the units actually

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:50.080
make sense.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.200
That I'm not
saying, three apples

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:55.000
are less than four oranges.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.870
So k1, it's first
order, so the units

00:08:57.870 --> 00:09:01.950
are one over second. k2, it's
a second order rate constant,

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:07.534
so the units are one over second
molar, times moles per liter.

00:09:07.534 --> 00:09:08.950
So the moles per
liters cancel out

00:09:08.950 --> 00:09:10.920
and I have one over our second
is less than one over second,

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:12.160
so things are great.

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:15.320
It I'm making the right
kind of approximation here.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.110
What else is this
approximation saying?

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:23.650
This is saying that the
rate into B, so this one is

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:26.670
the faster one. k1, the rate
into B, is the rate into,

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:32.580
is k1, is faster than k2 times
A, which is basically the rate

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:41.055
into C. So this is saying that
the rate into B, to form B,

00:09:41.055 --> 00:09:53.250
is faster than into C. So
we can write down a sketch.

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:57.970
We can sketch what we expect
this approximation to be, then.

00:09:57.970 --> 00:10:04.370
And we know it's going to
look something like this.

00:10:04.370 --> 00:10:10.290
We know that A is going to
come down, exponentially.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:11.938
Without any structure to it.

00:10:11.938 --> 00:10:13.646
It's going to go either
into B or into C,

00:10:13.646 --> 00:10:15.840
in some branching fractions.

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:19.430
And we know that the rate
into B is faster than into C,

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:22.440
so B is going to
come up like this.

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:27.510
And C is going to
come up, but slower.

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:34.660
And there's going to be a
ratio between these two guys.

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:37.400
So we know the slope here
is going to be slower

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:40.140
then the slope for B. And
we can check that out,

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:41.980
within our approximation.

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:47.511
We can write, at t
equals zero, find out

00:10:47.511 --> 00:10:48.760
what these initial slopes are.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:52.780
For the creation of
B and C. So dB/dt

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:58.150
is the slope of the creation
of B at the beginning.

00:10:58.150 --> 00:11:02.930
At t equals zero.

00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:05.740
And that's just the
rate law. dB/dt at t

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:11.830
equals zero is k1 A0.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:21.320
And dC/dt, the initial slope, t
equals zero, is k1 A0 squared.

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:28.430
Or k2 A0 squared, rather.

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:36.890
So I'm going to write it as
k2 A0 squared, like this.

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:40.130
We said k1 is much
bigger than k2 times A0.

00:11:40.130 --> 00:11:41.870
There's the same A0 here.

00:11:41.870 --> 00:11:43.730
So we see, just by
writing this down,

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:48.904
that our intuition that
because the rate into B

00:11:48.904 --> 00:11:51.320
is much faster than into A,
that it should look like this.

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:54.700
Well it's borne out just
like this very simple sort

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:58.640
of looking at the initial
rate where the slope here

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:04.220
is much smaller
than the slope here.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:10.240
And then we can take the
approximation in here.

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:13.330
And see what it implies.

00:12:13.330 --> 00:12:18.100
So let me do that here, let me
just use my green chalk here.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:21.520
So k2 A0 is much less than k1.

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:27.760
So this is going to go away.
k2 A0 is much less than k1.

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:29.260
Well, this is
building up from zero.

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:31.530
So this is always
bigger than one here.

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:33.171
So I can get rid
of this as well.

00:12:33.171 --> 00:12:34.670
Because there's the
k1 sitting here.

00:12:34.670 --> 00:12:39.100
And k1 is much
bigger than k2 A0.

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:44.280
Once I got rid of all these two
guys, then the k1's cancel out.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:45.980
And this is looking very nice.

00:12:45.980 --> 00:12:50.110
Because now I can take that e
to the k1 t and put it upstairs.

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:56.380
A is equal to approximately
A0 e to the minus k1 times

00:12:56.380 --> 00:13:00.320
time in this approximation.

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.870
It looks like it's
first order coming down,

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:05.670
with a rate constant k1.

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:10.250
It looks like basically
the branching into C

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:13.874
is nonexistent as far as, at
least in this approximation,

00:13:13.874 --> 00:13:14.790
as far A is concerned.

00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:19.970
It's going to look
like this thing here.

00:13:19.970 --> 00:13:23.650
It's going to look
like first order

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:26.120
A goes to B with
rate constant k1.

00:13:26.120 --> 00:13:28.330
So if you didn't
know, if you didn't

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:30.520
know that there was
another substance, C,

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:33.290
that was being formed along the
way, if you didn't measure it,

00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:35.990
if you didn't do the analytical
chemistry and sort of fish it

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:41.870
out, and you just looked at the
two major components, A and B,

00:13:41.870 --> 00:13:45.130
in this case here, you'd
measure a rate out of A,

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:48.110
it would look like
it's first order.

00:13:48.110 --> 00:13:50.380
It's great.

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:51.220
Got my mechanism.

00:13:51.220 --> 00:13:54.150
A goes to B, period.

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:57.195
And you would know there
was a minor component that

00:13:57.195 --> 00:14:02.050
was being formed
at the same time.

00:14:02.050 --> 00:14:15.560
OK, let's do another
approximation.

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:24.917
Let's do the other case, where
k2 A0 is much bigger than k1.

00:14:24.917 --> 00:14:26.500
And, in this case
here, you have to be

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:27.583
a little bit more careful.

00:14:27.583 --> 00:14:30.780
You have to add
that you're going

00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:32.300
to look at this at early times.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:36.240
And we're going to see why
early times is important here.

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:38.610
In just five minutes.

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:41.180
And early times, and how
you define early times.

00:14:41.180 --> 00:14:44.000
What does it mean for things to
be close to time equals zero?

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.250
Well, we have to have
a reference time scale.

00:14:48.250 --> 00:14:51.690
The reactions, I'm
going at a certain rate.

00:14:51.690 --> 00:14:54.150
And one second may be very slow.

00:14:54.150 --> 00:14:55.120
Or it may be very fast.

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.640
Depending on the
rate of the reaction.

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:03.220
So k1 here defines the
time scale of the problem.

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:06.640
It's one over second,
unit of one over second.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:10.250
And early times means that
the times that I'm looking at

00:15:10.250 --> 00:15:15.620
compare to this rate,
it's very small.

00:15:15.620 --> 00:15:19.960
So k1 t is less than one.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:23.520
That means that the time,
during the time period that I'm

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:28.680
looking at, hardly anything has
happened to the branching of A

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:32.360
to B. That that's what
I mean by early time.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:36.910
So B is hardly being built
up yet. k1 is our reference

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:40.590
time. k1 is units
of one over second.

00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:42.480
This has units of seconds.

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:45.025
So it's all working out fine.

00:15:45.025 --> 00:15:47.650
In other words, I would have no
idea how to define early times.

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.590
I could say, it's in
a year, it could be,

00:15:49.590 --> 00:15:51.320
if you're looking
at plutonium decay,

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:53.850
it's a 100,000 year half-life.

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:55.460
A year would be an early time.

00:15:55.460 --> 00:15:58.760
So it would be really fast,
compared to the process.

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:01.075
But if you're looking
at a reaction that

00:16:01.075 --> 00:16:04.450
takes a few nanoseconds than a
year would be very, very long.

00:16:04.450 --> 00:16:06.430
So you really need
your reference time

00:16:06.430 --> 00:16:11.030
somewhere in there.

00:16:11.030 --> 00:16:13.910
So this approximation means
that essentially, no B

