00:31:53.840 --> 00:31:57.740
And so, and at
time to equal zero,

00:31:57.740 --> 00:32:01.870
B0 is equal to zero because we
haven't made any intermediates.

00:32:01.870 --> 00:32:06.480
So this goes away.

00:32:06.480 --> 00:32:08.410
And then we have an equals sign.

00:32:08.410 --> 00:32:15.079
And on the other side, we
have k1 A0 over k2 minus k1,

00:32:15.079 --> 00:32:16.620
it's just the integral
of this thing,

00:32:16.620 --> 00:32:21.580
here with a k2 minus k1
goes in the denominator. e

00:32:21.580 --> 00:32:28.290
to the k2 minus k1
times time minus one.

00:32:28.290 --> 00:32:33.150
So now you have your integral
form for the amount of B

00:32:33.150 --> 00:32:36.820
that gets created at any time.

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:38.980
And I want to keep
that on the board.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:40.540
Because I'm going
to use it later.

00:32:40.540 --> 00:32:52.250
k1 A0 over k1 minus k2 times
e to the minus k1 times

00:32:52.250 --> 00:33:01.810
time minus e to the
minus k2 times time.

00:33:01.810 --> 00:33:03.770
OK, we're two thirds
of the way through.

00:33:03.770 --> 00:33:10.080
Now we've got to find C.
And for the last component,

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:12.290
you don't want to be
doing this kind of stuff.

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:14.830
You don't want to waste your
time solving differential

00:33:14.830 --> 00:33:20.082
equations, because
stoichiometry can help you out.

00:33:20.082 --> 00:33:22.040
At the end of the day,
you know that everything

00:33:22.040 --> 00:33:25.340
that started out as A,
in terms of quantities,

00:33:25.340 --> 00:33:28.240
is going to end up at C.
You know that if you end up

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:31.220
with a concentration
A0 at the beginning,

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.440
at the end of the process
the concentration of C,

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:37.210
at infinite time, is
also going to be A0.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:41.470
If you know that
there's a correlation,

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:46.130
there's a stoichiometry that
relates A and C together.

00:33:46.130 --> 00:33:53.200
And B. You have conservation
of mass here, basically.

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:55.430
Conservation of atoms.

00:33:55.430 --> 00:33:58.610
That has to come into play

00:33:58.610 --> 00:34:07.870
So, for C, we're just going to
do algebra instead of calculus.

00:34:07.870 --> 00:34:10.620
So let's write down
the stoichiometry here.

00:34:10.620 --> 00:34:15.370
The amount of C at
any time is what

00:34:15.370 --> 00:34:17.200
it's going to be at the end.

00:34:17.200 --> 00:34:19.600
Which is A0, very
end of the process.

00:34:19.600 --> 00:34:21.240
It's going to be A0.

00:34:21.240 --> 00:34:24.530
But before we get
to the end, there's

00:34:24.530 --> 00:34:28.346
still stuff that's
left in A and B.

00:34:28.346 --> 00:34:30.220
And that's going to
decrease the amount of C.

00:34:30.220 --> 00:34:35.660
So minus whatever's
still in A and B.

00:34:35.660 --> 00:34:37.712
That's the stoichiometry.

00:34:37.712 --> 00:34:38.920
That's one way of writing it.

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:40.711
You could also write
it in a different way.

00:34:40.711 --> 00:34:47.450
Which is that the amount of
C is equal to the amount of A

00:34:47.450 --> 00:34:50.240
that you have used up.

00:34:50.240 --> 00:34:53.270
A0 is what you started out with.

00:34:53.270 --> 00:34:54.350
A is what's left over.

00:34:54.350 --> 00:34:57.210
So this is the
amount of A used up.

00:34:57.210 --> 00:34:59.280
It's not all quite in C yet.

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:02.510
Some of it is stuck in B.

00:35:02.510 --> 00:35:06.060
So it's the amount of A used
up, minus the amount that's

00:35:06.060 --> 00:35:09.330
stuck in B. Those
two are the same.

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:10.580
I hope.

00:35:10.580 --> 00:35:12.220
A0 minus A, yeah, that's right.

00:35:12.220 --> 00:35:13.940
Minus B, yeah, that's right.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:18.180
So this is used up.

00:35:18.180 --> 00:35:26.770
And then stuck in B.
That's the hard part.

00:35:26.770 --> 00:35:29.080
Putting down the stoichiometry.

00:35:29.080 --> 00:35:30.710
Once you've done
the hard part, then

00:35:30.710 --> 00:35:32.180
if you solve the other
two then it's easy.

00:35:32.180 --> 00:35:32.888
You just plug in.

00:35:32.888 --> 00:35:35.210
It's just algebra.

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:37.910
And you get something
complicated.

00:35:37.910 --> 00:35:43.920
C is equal to complicated.

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:49.110
It's in the notes, I'm not
going to write it down.

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:51.680
So we've solved the
problem exactly.

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:53.389
And now you're going
to do an experiment.

00:35:53.389 --> 00:35:54.930
And the experiment
you're going to do

00:35:54.930 --> 00:35:57.100
is not going to follow
this whole thing, exactly.

00:35:57.100 --> 00:35:59.840
It's going to look
at limited cases.

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:02.560
That's what you can do.

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:04.020
And so the first
thing to look at

00:36:04.020 --> 00:36:06.140
is to look at the initial times.

00:36:06.140 --> 00:36:07.840
The very beginning
of the process,

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:11.180
how are things appearing.

00:36:11.180 --> 00:36:33.240
And then we'll look
at the late times.

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:35.940
So initial times.

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:46.040
Near t equals zero.

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:50.780
Well, every one of these things
has an exponential in it.

00:36:50.780 --> 00:36:53.470
And whenever we see exponentials
and we look at something

00:36:53.470 --> 00:36:57.040
at the early times, times that
are faster than one over k1,

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:02.940
or faster than one over k2, it
tells us use a Taylor series.

00:37:02.940 --> 00:37:06.210
So use the approximation
e to the minus kt

00:37:06.210 --> 00:37:14.510
is approximately equal to
one minus kt plus kt squared

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:16.110
over two plus et cetera.

00:37:16.110 --> 00:37:20.040
And keep as many terms as
you need in the Taylor series

00:37:20.040 --> 00:37:21.640
to get something sensible.

00:37:21.640 --> 00:37:23.610
So if everything comes
out of zero at the end,

00:37:23.610 --> 00:37:26.210
you know you haven't
kept enough terms in t.

00:37:26.210 --> 00:37:28.110
Things have canceled
out too much.

00:37:28.110 --> 00:37:31.010
And you want something
that is time dependent.

00:37:31.010 --> 00:37:33.210
Because you've got a
change in time, right?

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:36.330
It's a very common mistake
to say only keep one here

00:37:36.330 --> 00:37:38.680
and then everything
cancels out you get zero,

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:41.940
and you say, well, B is
equal to zero at all times.

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:46.390
That's nonsensical.

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:49.330
And I don't know a priori
how much time to keep.

00:37:49.330 --> 00:37:53.340
So let's go to second order.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:38:00.150
So if you plug this
Taylor series into A,

00:38:00.150 --> 00:38:02.230
and get something
that's time dependent,

00:38:02.230 --> 00:38:04.070
you only need to
go to first order.

00:38:04.070 --> 00:38:08.850
One minus k1 times
time plus et cetera.

00:38:08.850 --> 00:38:14.000
Plug it into b, plug your
Taylor series into these two

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:22.450
guys here, get k1
A0 over k2 minus k1,

00:38:22.450 --> 00:38:24.640
you only need it to
go to first order.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:27.720
The one's cancel out but
the times don't cancel out.

00:38:27.720 --> 00:38:33.160
Minus k1 plus k2, that is,
unless k1 and k2 are the same.

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:35.130
So we're making
the approximation

00:38:35.130 --> 00:38:38.930
that k1 is different than k2.

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:41.430
Times the time.

00:38:41.430 --> 00:38:43.780
And when we look at C,
this complicated thing

00:38:43.780 --> 00:38:46.680
that I didn't write
down, if you were just

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:50.832
to stop at first order in
C, you get C equals zero.

00:38:50.832 --> 00:38:52.040
You know that can't be right.

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:55.036
You know that C is going
to increase in time.

00:38:55.036 --> 00:38:56.660
It can't be equal to
zero at all times.

00:38:56.660 --> 00:39:00.950
So we have to go to
second order for C0.

00:39:00.950 --> 00:39:08.560
And it's approximately equal to
A0 times k1 k2 over two times

00:39:08.560 --> 00:39:11.459
the time squared.

00:39:11.459 --> 00:39:13.250
Let me rewrite this a
little bit closer in,

00:39:13.250 --> 00:39:15.450
because I need some room here.

00:39:15.450 --> 00:39:20.540
So c is approximately
equal to A0 k1

00:39:20.540 --> 00:39:24.807
is k2 over two
times time squared.

00:39:24.807 --> 00:39:26.390
OK, and then we can
start plotting out

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:27.931
what this is going
to look like then.

